      <h1>Toyoda–Germanov lineage</h1>
      <p class="concept-hero-subtitle">Technical precision, inner discipline, and continuity of transmission.</p>
    </div>

    <p class="news-meta">March 7, 2026</p>

    <p>
      When we speak about our line of practice,
      we do not mean an organizational label.
      We mean a concrete training methodology
      that combines the legacy of Fumio Toyoda
      with the consistent teaching of Shihan Edvard Germanov.
    </p>

    <p>
      The core of this method rests on three elements:
      technical precision,
      inner discipline,
      and instructor accountability for transmission quality.
    </p>

    <h2>How this appears on the mat</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Clear entry intent:</strong> taking initiative instead of collecting technique after the attack.</li>
      <li><strong>Control of axis and balance:</strong> less forceful pressure, more directional structure.</li>
      <li><strong>Action closure:</strong> technique does not end at the throw—full completion matters.</li>
      <li><strong>Ukemi quality:</strong> a truth test of technical clarity and dojo culture, not only safety.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Compared with other Aikido streams</h2>
    <p>
      This line remains rooted in classical Aikido heritage,
      yet has its own profile:
      strong budō orientation,
      high standards of breath and presence work,
      and explicit quality criteria for instructors.
      It is less performative,
      more craft-based,
      and long-term by design.
    </p>

    <h2>The role of the teacher</h2>
    <p>
      In this perspective, a teacher is not only a commentator of techniques,
      but a guardian of principles.
      They ensure technique stays connected to fundamentals,
      and that inner work does not degrade into empty declarations.
      This is how students progress not only in rank,
      but in quality and ethics.
    </p>

    <h2>Conclusion</h2>
    <p>
      The Toyoda–Germanov line is for people
      who seek more than movement aesthetics in Aikido.
      It is a demanding path,
      yet stable and coherent:
      combining effectiveness,
      self-discipline,
      and mature guidance of the training process.
    </p>
